    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sorting, searching, traversal, and merge patterns appear throughout agent code — ranking retrieved documents, finding tools by name, walking dependency graphs, and merging context streams. Knowing standard algorithms avoids reinventing buggy variants under time pressure."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What it is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "algorithm",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is a step-by-step procedure to solve a class of problems. Agent systems commonly use sorting, binary search, BFS/DFS graph traversal, merge of sorted lists, deduplication, and top-k selection."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why it matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reranking retrieval hits, selecting the top-k chunks for context, traversing a repo tree for a coding agent, or merging streaming tool outputs all map to well-studied algorithms with known complexity and edge cases."
          }
        ]
      },
